# Game Design Portfolio Mastery: Character Sheets vs. Corporate Reality

This document synthesizes our exploration into modern game design portfolios. It maps the tension between **Creative Expression** (your Character Sheet theme) and **Professional Utility** (hiring manager requirements).

---

## 1. The Strategy: "Snippy" vs. "Article"
The age-old question: *How much should I talk about myself?*

### The "Flavor Text" Hierarchy
*   **The Snippy Hook (Lvl 1):** Essential for landing pages. It establishes your "Creative Identity" in under 5 seconds.
*   **The Skill Tree (Lvl 2):** 1-2 paragraphs or bulleted pillars. This is where you prove competence. It shouldn't be about dreams; it should be about **methodology**.
*   **The Manifest (Lvl 3):** Detailed articles/dev logs. These should be **external or optional**. They build "Authority" but can clutter your "Identity."

> [!TIP]
> **Source:** *Liz England (Lead Designer at Insomniac/Saints Row)* suggests designers should focus on "The Why." While she doesn't explicitly mandate length, her influence on the industry (The Door Problem) proves that **clarity of thought** beats **volume of text**.

---

## 2. The 3-Persona Protocol
Every time someone clicks your site, they are playing a different "Class." Your UI must serve all three.

| Persona | Goal | Success Metric |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **The Recruiter** | Filter out non-qualified leads. | Find Resume & Tools in < 30 seconds. |
| **The Hiring Manager** | Assess culture fit and stability. | Does this person "finish" their vision? |
| **The Lead Designer** | Assess technical & systemic depth. | Do they understand *The Why* behind a mechanic? |

### Validation of the "Character Sheet" Layout
*   **Green Flag:** Using a theme (Character Sheet) proves you can execute a **Visual Bible**. It is a "hidden project" that demonstrates UI/UX skills.
*   **Red Flag:** If the theme obscures the **System Utility** (the Exit/Contact/Resume buttons). 

---

## 3. The "Pure" Character Sheet: UX Validation
You decided to keep the Character Sheet "informative only" and leave links in the Header/Contact panel. This is a **Senior Design Move.**

### Why this works (Separation of Concerns):
1.  **Mental Models:** Users expect "About" to be an identity-check and "Header" to be a navigation-check. Mixing them creates "Cognitive Friction."
2.  **Immersive UI:** Keeping the Sheet "pure" allows it to function as a narrative device, proving you understand **Ludonarrative Harmony.**
3.  **Hierarchy of Needs:** At the base of the portfolio "Hierarchy of Needs" (inspired by Riot Games' advice) is **Discoverability.** By putting links in a global header, you satisfy the base need, allowing the Character Sheet to satisfy higher-level needs like "Personality."

---

## 4. In-Depth Insights & Credibility Frameworks

### The "Door Problem" (Foundational Knowledge)
*   **Source:** [The Door Problem - Liz England](https://www.lizengland.com/blog/2014/04/the-door-problem/)
*   **Insight:** A game designer’s job isn't just "having ideas"; it's solving the thousands of tiny system problems (e.g., "Can the player open the door? Is it locked? Does it need an animation?"). 
*   **Portfolio Application:** Your "Logs" and "Talents" should reflect this type of thinking. Don't say "I like RPGs." Say "I design systems for lock-and-key progression."

### Cursed Problems & Player Mythologies
*   **Source:** [Alex Jaffe (Riot Games) - Cursed Problems GDC Talk](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8uE67pEcVrk)
*   **Insight:** Good design is about navigating unsolvable conflicts (e.g., "Complexity vs. Accessibility"). 
*   **Portfolio Application:** In your "Philosophy" section, briefly mention how you handle **"Cursed Problems."** It shows a Lead Designer that you are thinking at a Master's level.

---

## 5. Resources for Further Mastery

### Critical Reading
*   **[Riot Games: Portfolio Advice](https://www.riotgames.com/en/work-with-us/disciplines/design/design-portfolio-advice):** The gold standard for what a AAA studio expects.
*   **[Victoria Tran: Portfolio Tips](https://www.victoriatran.com/writing/portfolio-tips):** Focuses on narrative and community-driven design portfolios.
*   **[The Design of Everyday Things (Don Norman)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Design_of_Everyday_Things):** The foundation of UX. If you understand "Affordances" and "Signifiers," your portfolio will naturally be better.

### Searchable Examples of "Themed" Portfolios
*   **"Interactive Game Design Portfolios" (Behance/Awwwards):** Look for people who use "Scanlines" or "Terminal UI." Note how they always keep a "Normal" menu available for the Recruiters.
*   **"GDD Templates 2024":** Use these to see how professional documentation is structured so you can copy the "flavor" of that professional language into your "Talents" tab.

---

**Closing Thought:** You are currently building a **"Player Methodology."** By treating your portfolio like a game system, you aren't just *telling* them you are a game designer; you are *letting them play* the role of your employer. Stick to the 3-tab structure and keep your "Lore" concise. 
